10 An Act relating to medical records; amending 76 O.S.
2021, Section 19, which relates to access to medical
11 records; modifying applicability of certain
provisions; eliminating certain duties of health care
12 providers; authorizing imposition of certain fees;
modifying certain fee limits; defining terms; making
13 certain acts unlawful; creating misdemeanor offense;
providing administrative and criminal penalties;
14 providing for civil relief; updating statutory
language; and providing an effective date.
15
16
17 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
18 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 76 O.S. 2021, Section 19, is
19 amended to read as follows:
20 Section 19. A. 1. Any person who is or has been a patient of
21 a doctor, hospital or other medical institution health care provider
22 or health care facility, or such person’s personal representative,
23 shall, as provided under 45 C.F.R., Section 164.502, be entitled,
24 upon request, to obtain access to the information contained in the
Req. No. 1755 Page 1
1 pati ent’s medical records including any x-ray or other photograph or
2 image, pathology slide, or the patient’s medical bills.
3 2. Disclosure of the information described in paragraph 1 of
4 this subsection regarding a deceased patient shall require either a
5 court order or a written release of an executor, administrator, or
6 personal representative appointed by the court, or if there is no
7 such appointment, by the spouse of the patient or, if none, by any
8 responsible family member of the family of the patient. As used in
9 this paragraph, “responsible family member” shall mean the parent,
10 adult child, adult sibling, or other adult relative who was actively
11 involved in providing care to or monitoring the care of the patient
12 as verified by the doctor, hospital or other medical institution
13 health care provider or health care facility responsible for the
14 care and treatment of such person.
15 2. Any person who is or has been a patient of a doctor,
16 hospital or other medical institution shall be furnished copies of
17 all medical records including any x-ray, other photograph or image,
18 pathology slide or all medical bills pertaining to that person’s
19 case upon request and upon the tender of the expenses enumerated in
20 this paragraph. The cost of each copy to such person or to the
21 personal representative, spouse or responsible family member of such
22 person, not including any x-ray or other photograph or image or
23 pathology slide, shall be fifty cents ($0.50) for each page.
24
Req. No. 1755 Page 2
1 3. A health care provider or health care facility may impose a
2 reasonable, cost-based fee when patients or their personal
3 representatives request copies of medical records; provided, that
4 the fee includes only the cost of applicable expenses listed in 42
5 C.F.R., Section 164.524(c)(4).
6 4. Requests for medical records and medical bills from, or
7 directed to, attorneys, insurance companies, other third parties,
8 and by way of subpoena shall be charged a base fee of Twenty Dollars
9 ($20.00) Twenty-three Dollars ($23.00) in addition to the a per page
10 charges required pursuant to this section fee of:
11 a. sixty-seven cents ($0.67) for paper copies, plus
12 postage or delivery fee, or
13 b. forty cents ($0.40) for electronic copies.
14 The base fee shall be charged regardless of whether any records
15 related to the request are located. A fee of Fifteen Dollars
16 ($15.00) shall be charged if a certification or an affidavit by the
17 provider regarding the authenticity of the medical records or bills
18 is requested. The physician, hospital or other medical
19 professionals and institutions, or their business associates as the
20 term is defined in Section 160.103 of Title 45 of the United States
21 Code of Federal Regulations shall produce the records in digital
22 form at the rate of thirty cents ($0.30) per page if:
23 a. the entire request can be reproduced from an
24 electronic health record system,
Req. No. 1755 Page 3
1 b. the records are specifically requested to be delivered
2 in electronic format, and
3 c. the records can be delivered electronically.
4 If a provider or business associate transmits the records
5 electronically, no postage shall be charged but a delivery charge
6 shall apply. In no event shall a charge for the reproduction of
7 electronically stored and delivered medical records pursuant to this
8 paragraph exceed Two Hundred Dollars ($200.00) Two Hundred Seventy
9 Dollars ($270.00) plus postage or delivery fee. The cost of each
10 printed x-ray, other photograph, or image to such person or to the
11 legal representative of such person shall be Fifteen Dollars
12 ($15.00). If the x-ray, other photograph, or image is provided on a
13 CD/DVD or other electronic media, the fee shall be Twenty Dollars
14 ($20.00) Twenty-three Dollars ($23.00) per CD/DVD or other
15 electronic media. The physician, hospital, or other medical
16 professionals and institutions, or their business associates as the
17 term is defined in Section 160.103 of Title 45 of the United States
18 Code of Federal Regulations, shall not charge a person who requests
19 their own record a fee for searching, retrieving, reviewing, and
20 preparing medical records of the person. No mailing fee shall be
21 charged for copies provided by facsimile. All requests for medical
22 records made pursuant to this subsection shall be subject to the
23 fees described in this section regardless of where the copies or
24 electronic versions of such records are actually produced.
Req. No. 1755 Page 4
1 3. 5. The provisions of paragraphs 1 and 2 of this subsection
2 shall not apply to:
3 a. psychological, psychiatric, mental health, or
4 substance abuse treatment records. In the case of
5 psychological, psychiatric, mental health, or
6 substance abuse treatment records, access to
7 information contained in the records shall be obtained
8 pursuant to Section 1-109 of Title 43A of the Oklahoma
9 Statutes.
10 4. The provisions of paragraphs 1 and 2 of this subsection
11 shall not apply to, and
12 b. requests for medical records made by the Disability
13 Determination Division of the State Department of
14 Rehabilitation Services. The fee for such requests
15 shall be at a rate allowed by the Social Security
16 Administration.
17 B. 1. In cases involving a claim for personal injury or death
18 against any practitioner of the healing arts or a licensed hospital,
19 or a nursing facility or nursing home licensed pursuant to Section
20 1-1903 of Title 63 of the Oklahoma Statutes arising out of patient
21 care, where any person has placed the physical or mental condition
22 of that person in issue by the commencement of any action,
23 proceeding, or suit for damages, or where any person has placed in
24 issue the physical or mental condition of any other person or
Req. No. 1755 Page 5
1 dece ased person by or through whom the person rightfully claims,
2 that person shall be deemed to waive any privilege granted by law
3 concerning any communication made to a physician or health care
4 provider with reference to any physical or mental condition or any
5 knowledge obtained by the physician or health care provider by
6 personal examination of the patient; provided that, before any
7 communication, medical or hospital record, or testimony is admitted
8 in evidence in any proceeding, it must be material and relevant to
9 an issue therein, according to existing rules of evidence.
10 Psychological, psychiatric, mental health, and substance abuse
11 treatment records and information from psychological, psychiatric,
12 mental health, and substance abuse treatment practitioners may only
13 be obtained provided the requirements of Section 1-109 of Title 43A
14 of the Oklahoma Statutes are met.
15 2. Any person who obtains any document pursuant to the
16 provisions of this section shall provide copies of the document to
17 any opposing party in the proceeding upon payment of the expense of
18 copying the document pursuant to the provisions of this section.
19 C. This section shall not apply to the records of an inmate in
20 a correctional institution when the correctional institution
21 believes the release of such information to be a threat to the
22 safety or security of the inmate or the institution.
23 D. 1. As used in this section, the terms “covered entity” and
24 “protected health information” shall have the same meaning as
Req. No. 1755 Page 6
1 prov ided under the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability
2 Act of 1996 (HIPAA).
3 2. It shall be unlawful for a covered entity to use or disclose
4 protected health information except as authorized under HIPAA.
5 3. Intentional violation of paragraph 2 of this subsection
6 shall be deemed unprofessional conduct by the covered entity’s
7 licensure board or regulatory agency if applicable and subject to
8 mandatory license revocation.
9 4. A covered entity found in violation of paragraph 2 of this
10 subsection shall, upon conviction, be guilty of a misdemeanor
11 punishable by a fine not to exceed One Thousand Dollars ($1,000.00).
12 5. If a covered entity believes a violation of paragraph 2 of
13 this subsection has occurred or will occur in relation to a request
14 for medical records, the covered entity may apply to a court of
15 competent jurisdiction for relief and the court shall award
16 appropriate relief including, but not limited to, temporary,
17 preliminary, or permanent injunctive relief.
18 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2025.
